{"ts": "2026-04-04T14:55:16.676", "event": "PostToolUse:raw_input", "raw_input": {"session_id": "40302fac-b037-4b24-b2d0-deb954ba8d45", "transcript_path": "/home/emhar/.claude/projects/-home-emhar-avaris-ai/40302fac-b037-4b24-b2d0-deb954ba8d45.jsonl", "cwd": "/home/emhar/avaris-ai", "permission_mode": "plan", "hook_event_name": "PostToolUse", "tool_name": "Agent", "tool_input": {"description": "Design JSONL session state migration", "prompt": "Design an implementation plan for migrating from a single `state.json` to a session-scoped `state.jsonl` file in the Claude hooks workflow system.\n\n## Current Architecture\n\n### State Files\n- **`state.json`** at `.claude/hooks/workflow/state.json` \u2014 single flat JSON object shared by ALL sessions\n- **`config/paths.py`** defines `DEFAULT_STATE_PATH = WORKFLOW_ROOT / \"state.json\"`\n\n### State Classes\n- **`StateStore`** (`state_store.py`) \u2014 Base class, wraps a single JSON file with file-locking via `FileManager`\n  - Methods: load(), save(), update(fn), get(key), set(key, value), reset(), reinitialize(), delete(), archive()\n  - Uses `FileManager` with `filelock.FileLock` for atomic read-modify-write\n  \n- **`SessionState`** (`session_state.py`) \u2014 Extends `StateStore`, adds typed properties/setters for workflow fields\n  - Currently: if no session_id \u2192 uses DEFAULT_STATE_PATH (global); if session_id \u2192 `.claude/sessions/session_{id}/state.json`\n  - Has `get_default_state()` returning the full schema template\n\n### Consumers (ALL use global `state.json` today)\n1. **Dispatchers** (6 files in `dispatchers/`): Each creates `StateStore(DEFAULT_STATE_PATH)` inline\n   - `pre_tool_use.py`, `post_tool_use.py`, `session_start.py`, `subagent_start.py`, `subagent_stop.py`, `user_prompt_submit.py`\n2. **Guards** (9 files in `guards/`): Receive `store: StateStore` as parameter from guardrail.py\n3. **`guardrail.py`**: Creates `StateStore(state_path)` in `_dispatch()`, env var `GUARDRAIL_STATE_PATH` override\n4. **`recorder.py`**: Creates `StateStore(state_path)` in `_dispatch()`, env var `RECORDER_STATE_PATH` override\n5. **`reminder.py`**: Receives `store: StateStore` as parameter\n6. **`auto_commit.py`**: Reads `DEFAULT_STATE_PATH` for story_id context\n7. **`lib/build_entry.py`**: Creates `StateStore(PATH)` for workflow activation\n\n### Hook Input\nEvery hook event's stdin JSON includes `\"session_id\": \"<uuid>\"` \u2014 this is the Claude session UUID.\n\n## Requirements\n- Migrate from single `state.json` to `state.jsonl` where each line is a separate session's state\n- Each JSON line has the same schema as current `state.json` but with `session_id` field added\n- Sessions must not affect each other\n- File locking must still work for concurrent access\n- All existing consumers must work with the new format\n\n## Design Constraints\n- Keep it simple \u2014 the user prefers lean approaches\n- `state.jsonl` lives at the same location: `.claude/hooks/workflow/state.jsonl`\n- The `session_id` comes from hook stdin input (always available as UUID)\n- Guards receive `store` as parameter \u2014 they don't need to change if the store API stays the same\n- Guardrail and recorder are the main entry points that create StateStore instances\n\n## Questions to Address\n1. How should `StateStore` be modified (or replaced) to handle JSONL with session-scoped access?\n2. What's the cleanest way to thread `session_id` through from dispatchers \u2192 guardrail/recorder \u2192 guards?\n3. Should we create a new `SessionStore` class or modify `StateStore`?\n4. How does file locking work with JSONL (rewriting entire file vs appending)?\n5. What happens to `SessionState` class \u2014 does it wrap the new store?\n\nPlease provide a detailed implementation plan with specific file changes.", "subagent_type": "Plan"}, "tool_response": {"status": "completed", "prompt": "Design an implementation plan for migrating from a single `state.json` to a session-scoped `state.jsonl` file in the Claude hooks workflow system.\n\n## Current Architecture\n\n### State Files\n- **`state.json`** at `.claude/hooks/workflow/state.json` \u2014 single flat JSON object shared by ALL sessions\n- **`config/paths.py`** defines `DEFAULT_STATE_PATH = WORKFLOW_ROOT / \"state.json\"`\n\n### State Classes\n- **`StateStore`** (`state_store.py`) \u2014 Base class, wraps a single JSON file with file-locking via `FileManager`\n  - Methods: load(), save(), update(fn), get(key), set(key, value), reset(), reinitialize(), delete(), archive()\n  - Uses `FileManager` with `filelock.FileLock` for atomic read-modify-write\n  \n- **`SessionState`** (`session_state.py`) \u2014 Extends `StateStore`, adds typed properties/setters for workflow fields\n  - Currently: if no session_id \u2192 uses DEFAULT_STATE_PATH (global); if session_id \u2192 `.claude/sessions/session_{id}/state.json`\n  - Has `get_default_state()` returning the full schema template\n\n### Consumers (ALL use global `state.json` today)\n1. **Dispatchers** (6 files in `dispatchers/`): Each creates `StateStore(DEFAULT_STATE_PATH)` inline\n   - `pre_tool_use.py`, `post_tool_use.py`, `session_start.py`, `subagent_start.py`, `subagent_stop.py`, `user_prompt_submit.py`\n2. **Guards** (9 files in `guards/`): Receive `store: StateStore` as parameter from guardrail.py\n3. **`guardrail.py`**: Creates `StateStore(state_path)` in `_dispatch()`, env var `GUARDRAIL_STATE_PATH` override\n4. **`recorder.py`**: Creates `StateStore(state_path)` in `_dispatch()`, env var `RECORDER_STATE_PATH` override\n5. **`reminder.py`**: Receives `store: StateStore` as parameter\n6. **`auto_commit.py`**: Reads `DEFAULT_STATE_PATH` for story_id context\n7. **`lib/build_entry.py`**: Creates `StateStore(PATH)` for workflow activation\n\n### Hook Input\nEvery hook event's stdin JSON includes `\"session_id\": \"<uuid>\"` \u2014 this is the Claude session UUID.\n\n## Requirements\n- Migrate from single `state.json` to `state.jsonl` where each line is a separate session's state\n- Each JSON line has the same schema as current `state.json` but with `session_id` field added\n- Sessions must not affect each other\n- File locking must still work for concurrent access\n- All existing consumers must work with the new format\n\n## Design Constraints\n- Keep it simple \u2014 the user prefers lean approaches\n- `state.jsonl` lives at the same location: `.claude/hooks/workflow/state.jsonl`\n- The `session_id` comes from hook stdin input (always available as UUID)\n- Guards receive `store` as parameter \u2014 they don't need to change if the store API stays the same\n- Guardrail and recorder are the main entry points that create StateStore instances\n\n## Questions to Address\n1. How should `StateStore` be modified (or replaced) to handle JSONL with session-scoped access?\n2. What's the cleanest way to thread `session_id` through from dispatchers \u2192 guardrail/recorder \u2192 guards?\n3. Should we create a new `SessionStore` class or modify `StateStore`?\n4. How does file locking work with JSONL (rewriting entire file vs appending)?\n5. What happens to `SessionState` class \u2014 does it wrap the new store?\n\nPlease provide a detailed implementation plan with specific file changes.", "agentId": "acf466350d083856f", "agentType": "Plan", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "I now have a complete picture. Here is my implementation plan.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Plan: Migrate from `state.json` to Session-Scoped `state.jsonl`\n\n### Architecture Summary\n\nThe current system uses a single `state.json` file shared across all Claude sessions. Every dispatcher, guardrail, and recorder creates a `StateStore(DEFAULT_STATE_PATH)` pointing to this one file. The `session_id` is always present in hook stdin input but is never used for state scoping -- it is only stored as a data field inside the state dict.\n\nThe goal is to replace this with a single `state.jsonl` file where each line holds one session's state (keyed by `session_id`). This gives session isolation while keeping a single file (simpler than per-session directories).\n\n### Design Decisions\n\n**Q1: How should StateStore be modified?**\n\nDo NOT modify `StateStore`. Instead, create a new `JsonlSessionStore` class that wraps the JSONL file and exposes the exact same public API as `StateStore` (`load()`, `save()`, `update()`, `get()`, `set()`, `reset()`, `reinitialize()`, `delete()`, `archive()`). This is the safest approach -- existing code that receives a `store` parameter does not need to change at all.\n\n**Q2: How to thread session_id through?**\n\nThe `session_id` is already in every hook event's stdin JSON (as `raw_input[\"session_id\"]`). The dispatchers already parse `raw_input`. The change is: instead of `StateStore(DEFAULT_STATE_PATH)`, dispatchers call `JsonlSessionStore(DEFAULT_STATE_JSONL_PATH, session_id=raw_input[\"session_id\"])`. For guardrail/recorder (invoked as subprocesses), the `session_id` is already in the `--hook-input` JSON they receive, so they extract it from `hook_input[\"session_id\"]`.\n\n**Q3: New class or modify StateStore?**\n\nNew class: `JsonlSessionStore`. This keeps `StateStore` intact as a general-purpose JSON store (it is still useful for other files like `commit_batch.json`).\n\n**Q4: File locking with JSONL?**\n\nThe `JsonlSessionStore` uses a single `FileLock` on `state.jsonl.lock` (same pattern as current). On every read-modify-write cycle: acquire lock, read entire file, parse all lines, find the line matching `session_id`, operate on it, rewrite the entire file. This is the same atomicity model as today, just with a multi-record file. The file will be small (one line per active session, typically 1-5 sessions).\n\n**Q5: What happens to SessionState?**\n\n`SessionState` should be updated to extend `JsonlSessionStore` instead of `StateStore`. Its typed properties/setters remain unchanged -- they call `self.get()` and `self.set()` which are provided by the new base class. The `resolve_path()` function and per-session directory logic can be removed.\n\n### Step-by-Step Implementation\n\n#### Step 1: Create `JsonlSessionStore` class\n\n**File**: `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/jsonl_session_store.py` (new)\n\n```python\nclass JsonlSessionStore:\n    \"\"\"Session-scoped state store backed by a JSONL file.\n    \n    Each line in the JSONL file is a JSON object with a \"session_id\" field.\n    This class provides the same API as StateStore but operates on a single\n    session's line within the multi-session file.\n    \"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, jsonl_path: Path, session_id: str, default_state: dict | None = None):\n        self._path = jsonl_path\n        self._session_id = session_id\n        self._default_state = default_state or {}\n        self._lock = FileLock(jsonl_path.with_suffix(\".lock\"))\n```\n\nKey implementation details:\n- `_read_all_sessions()` -- reads file, returns `dict[str, dict]` mapping session_id to state dict (one JSON parse per line)\n- `_write_all_sessions(sessions: dict[str, dict])` -- writes all sessions back, one JSON line per session\n- `load()` -- acquires lock, reads all, returns this session's dict (or default_state if not found)\n- `save(state)` -- acquires lock, reads all, replaces this session's line, writes all\n- `update(fn)` -- acquires lock, reads all, applies fn to this session's dict, writes all\n- `get(key, default)` / `set(key, value)` -- convenience wrappers (same as StateStore)\n- `reset()` / `reinitialize()` / `delete()` -- operate on this session's entry only\n- `archive(history_path)` -- appends this session's state to history file (same as StateStore)\n\nThe critical invariant: every public method acquires the file lock, reads the whole file, modifies only the target session's line, and rewrites the whole file. This is safe for concurrent sessions.\n\n#### Step 2: Update `config/paths.py`\n\n**File**: `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/config/paths.py`\n\nAdd:\n```python\nDEFAULT_STATE_JSONL_PATH = WORKFLOW_ROOT / \"state.jsonl\"\n```\n\nKeep `DEFAULT_STATE_PATH` temporarily for backward compatibility during migration.\n\n#### Step 3: Update `guardrail.py` \n\n**File**: `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/guardrail.py`\n\nChange `_state_path()` and `_dispatch()`:\n- Extract `session_id` from `hook_input[\"session_id\"]`\n- Replace `StateStore(state_path)` with `JsonlSessionStore(state_jsonl_path, session_id)`\n- The `store` parameter passed to all guards is now a `JsonlSessionStore` instance, but since it has the same API, no guard changes needed\n\nSpecifically in `_dispatch()`:\n```python\ndef _dispatch(hook_input: dict, state_path: Path) -> tuple[str, str]:\n    session_id = hook_input.get(\"session_id\", \"default\")\n    store = JsonlSessionStore(state_path, session_id)\n    # ... rest unchanged\n```\n\n#### Step 4: Update `recorder.py`\n\n**File**: `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/recorder.py`\n\nSame change as guardrail -- in `_dispatch()` and `_state_path()`:\n- Extract `session_id` from `hook_input`\n- Create `JsonlSessionStore` instead of `StateStore`\n\n#### Step 5: Update all dispatchers (6 files)\n\nEach dispatcher that creates `StateStore(DEFAULT_STATE_PATH)` directly must switch to `JsonlSessionStore`. The `session_id` comes from `raw_input[\"session_id\"]`.\n\nFiles to change:\n1. `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/dispatchers/pre_tool_use.py` -- lines 75-78 where it creates `StateStore` for reminder injection\n2. `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/dispatchers/post_tool_use.py` -- lines 63, 72 where it creates `StateStore` for phase tracking and reminders\n3. `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/dispatchers/session_start.py` -- line 25 where it creates `StateStore`\n4. `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/dispatchers/subagent_start.py` -- line 20 where it creates `StateStore`\n5. `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/dispatchers/subagent_stop.py` -- line 54 where it creates `StateStore`\n6. `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/dispatchers/user_prompt_submit.py` -- line 48 where it creates `StateStore`\n\nPattern for each:\n```python\n# Before:\nstore = StateStore(DEFAULT_STATE_PATH)\n\n# After:\nfrom workflow.jsonl_session_store import JsonlSessionStore\nfrom workflow.config import DEFAULT_STATE_JSONL_PATH\nsession_id = raw_input.get(\"session_id\", \"default\")\nstore = JsonlSessionStore(DEFAULT_STATE_JSONL_PATH, session_id)\n```\n\n#### Step 6: Update `auto_commit.py`\n\n**File**: `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/auto_commit.py`\n\nThe `get_story_context()` function (line 178) reads `DEFAULT_STATE_PATH` directly with `json.loads`. This needs to be updated to:\n- Accept a `session_id` parameter (from `raw_input[\"session_id\"]`)\n- Use `JsonlSessionStore` to load the session's state\n\nAlternatively, since `auto_commit.py` only reads `story_id` and `tasks` from state, it can parse the JSONL file directly to find the matching session. However, using `JsonlSessionStore` is cleaner.\n\n#### Step 7: Update `lib/build_entry.py`\n\n**File**: `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/lib/build_entry.py`\n\nLine 19 creates `StateStore(STATE_PATH)` at module level. This needs a `session_id`. Since `build_entry.py` handles the `/build` command which spawns multiple sessions, it should either:\n- Use a \"default\" session_id for the orchestrator state, or\n- Not use session-scoped state at all (it just sets `workflow_active: True` as a global flag)\n\nRecommended: keep using `StateStore` for this specific file since it manages orchestrator-level (not session-level) state. This means `state.json` can coexist with `state.jsonl` -- the old file for orchestrator state, the new file for session state.\n\n#### Step 8: Update `SessionState`\n\n**File**: `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/session_state.py`\n\nChange to extend `JsonlSessionStore` instead of `StateStore`:\n```python\nclass SessionState(JsonlSessionStore):\n    def __init__(self, session_id: str):\n        super().__init__(DEFAULT_STATE_JSONL_PATH, session_id)\n```\n\nRemove the `resolve_path()` function and the fallback to `DEFAULT_STATE_PATH`. Every `SessionState` now requires a `session_id`.\n\n#### Step 9: Update `reminder.py`\n\n**File**: `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/reminder.py`\n\nNo changes needed. `reminder.py` receives `store: StateStore` as a parameter and calls `store.load()`, `store.set()`. Since `JsonlSessionStore` has the same API, it works transparently.\n\n#### Step 10: Update `workflow_initializer.py`\n\n**File**: `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/lib/workflow_initializer.py`\n\n`SessionState(session_id)` already passes session_id. After Step 8, this will use `JsonlSessionStore` under the hood. No changes needed beyond what Step 8 provides.\n\n#### Step 11: Migration helper\n\nAdd a one-time migration utility (can be a function in `jsonl_session_store.py`) that:\n1. Reads existing `state.json`\n2. If it has a `session_id` field, writes it as the first line of `state.jsonl` with that session_id\n3. If no `session_id`, writes it with key `\"default\"`\n4. Renames `state.json` to `state.json.bak`\n\nThis can be triggered on first access if `state.jsonl` does not exist but `state.json` does.\n\n#### Step 12: Update tests\n\n**Files**: \n- `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/tests/test_state_store.py` -- keep existing tests (StateStore still exists)\n- Create `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/tests/test_jsonl_session_store.py` -- new tests for JSONL store\n- `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/tests/conftest.py` -- update `mock_state_store` and `mock_session_state` fixtures\n- Update test files for guardrail, recorder, etc. that create `StateStore` directly\n\n### Guards -- No Changes Required\n\nAll 9 guard files receive `store: StateStore` as a parameter. Since `JsonlSessionStore` provides the same API (`load()`, `get()`, `set()`, `update()`), guards work without modification:\n- `agent_guard.py`, `bash_guard.py`, `read_guard.py`, `skill_guard.py`, `stop_guard.py`, `subagent_stop_guard.py`, `task_guard.py`, `webfetch_guard.py`, `write_guard.py`\n\n### File Locking Strategy\n\nThe JSONL approach uses a single lock file (`state.jsonl.lock`) for the entire file. Each operation:\n1. Acquires lock\n2. Reads all lines, parses each as JSON into a `dict[session_id, state_dict]`\n3. Operates on the target session's dict\n4. Serializes all sessions back (one JSON line per session, sorted by session_id for stability)\n5. Writes atomically (write to temp file, rename)\n6. Releases lock\n\nThis is safe because the file is small (under 10 sessions typically) and lock hold time is brief. The write-temp-then-rename pattern prevents corruption.\n\n### Potential Challenges\n\n1. **Subprocess boundary**: Dispatchers call guardrail/recorder as subprocesses via `python3 guardrail.py --hook-input '...'`. The `session_id` is already embedded in the hook input JSON, so it flows through naturally. No env var or extra CLI arg needed.\n\n2. **Backward compatibility**: The `build_entry.py` orchestrator and `auto_commit.py` read state.json directly. Build entry should keep using `StateStore` for orchestrator-level flags. Auto-commit needs explicit migration.\n\n3. **File size**: Each session state is roughly 500 bytes of JSON. With 5 concurrent sessions, the file is ~2.5KB. Not a concern.\n\n4. **Stale sessions**: Over time, completed sessions accumulate in the JSONL file. The `delete()` method removes a session's line. Consider adding a cleanup sweep (e.g., remove sessions older than 24h) as a future enhancement.\n\n### Critical Files for Implementation\n\n- `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/state_store.py` -- reference for API contract that `JsonlSessionStore` must match\n- `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/guardrail.py` -- primary entry point that creates store instances and passes them to guards\n- `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/recorder.py` -- second entry point that creates store instances for state mutations\n- `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/dispatchers/post_tool_use.py` -- representative dispatcher showing the pattern of inline `StateStore` creation\n- `/home/emhar/avaris-ai/.claude/hooks/workflow/session_state.py` -- typed wrapper that must switch base class from `StateStore` to `JsonlSessionStore`"}], "totalDurationMs": 127937, "totalTokens": 55073, "totalToolUseCount": 25, "usage": {"input_tokens": 1, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 804, "cache_read_input_tokens": 50510, "output_tokens": 3758, "server_tool_use": {"web_search_requests": 0, "web_fetch_requests": 0}, "service_tier": "standard", "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0, "ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 804}, "inference_geo": "", "iterations": [], "speed": "standard"}}, "tool_use_id": "toolu_01QViSPHriTDczsmkCuHnP5f"}}
